 However the consequent does not follow: what is at issue in this chapter
 is precisely the 
\emph on
higher order
\emph default
 behaviour of (6.46).
 For the linear response approximation to be valid one must require solutions
 to exist to arbitrary order in 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar$
\end_inset

 (though to only linear order in 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{a}$
\end_inset

).
 I believe that the claim that a contradiction exists (now arising at higher
 order in 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar$
\end_inset

) is still generally true.
 This is because of the second derivation of the contradiction given in
 (6.85)-(6.90) and the subsequent discussion.
 I cannot find any divergence or invalid step in this argument.
 Indeed, this derivation was given to avoid all such subtleties.
 Explicitly, the nontrivial components of (6.89), assuming the Goldstone
 sources vanish as discussed above, are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\delta\varphi_{g}\left(V_{GHG}v-\tilde{\Delta}_{H}^{-1}+\tilde{\Delta}_{G}^{-1}\right)+\mathcal{K}_{Ng}v,\\
\delta\varphi_{N}\tilde{\Delta}_{H}^{-1}+J_{N} & =-\delta\varphi_{N}\left(V_{HGG}v+\tilde{\Delta}_{G}^{-1}-\tilde{\Delta}_{H}^{-1}\right)-\mathcal{K}_{gg}v,\\
0 & =\mathcal{K}_{g'g},\\
\delta\varphi_{g}\tilde{\Delta}_{G}^{-1} & =0,
\end{align*}

