.
 The equations of motion are correct if the right hand sides vanish.
 To 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(\hbar^{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 the terms on the right hand side do indeed vanish.
 However, at higher orders the term in brackets in the first two equations
 (the vertex WI) is generically nonzero.
 This is in fact the original motivation for considering the SI-3PIEA.
 In order for the right hand side to vanish then, one must have a conspiratorial
 cancellation between the vertex WI term and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

 term.
 These quantities are logically independent.
 The only connection between them is mediated by the equations of motion.
 Therefore, such a cancellation seems highly nontrivial and truncation dependent.
 A full analysis of this scenario in a particular truncation requires computing
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}$
\end_inset

, which is found from 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\Delta^{-1}$
\end_inset

, which is found from (6.8), which requires solving the full system of linear
 response equations (6.9)-(6.12).
 Explicitly, the vanishing of the right hand sides becomes a set of conditions
 on the linear response functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{\phi J}$
\end_inset

 etc., which are the solutions of (6.9)-(6.12):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =\chi_{df}^{\phi J}\left(V_{dca}T_{ab}^{A}\tilde{\varphi}_{b}+\tilde{\Delta}_{ca}^{-1}T_{ad}^{A}+\tilde{\Delta}_{da}^{-1}T_{ac}^{A}\right)+\left(-\tilde{\Delta}_{cd}^{-1}\chi_{def}^{\Delta J}\tilde{\Delta}_{ea}^{-1}-V_{dca}\chi_{df}^{\phi J}\right)T_{ab}^{A}\tilde{\varphi}_{b},\\
0 & =\chi_{dfg}^{\phi K}\left(V_{dca}T_{ab}^{A}\tilde{\varphi}_{b}+\tilde{\Delta}_{ca}^{-1}T_{ad}^{A}+\tilde{\Delta}_{da}^{-1}T_{ac}^{A}\right)+\left(-\tilde{\Delta}_{cd}^{-1}\chi_{defg}^{\Delta K}\tilde{\Delta}_{ea}^{-1}-V_{dca}\chi_{dfg}^{\phi K}\right)T_{ab}^{A}\tilde{\varphi}_{b}.
\end{align*}

